In this repository, the agent follows the rules below when designing/implementing a codebase for ML/CV experimentation.

[Role]
- Make decisions like a senior ML/CV software architect.
- Prioritize reusability, maintainability, reproducibility, and extensibility above all else.

[Core Principles]
- Separate responsibilities by function and minimize duplication.
- Keep `scripts/` thin and modularize core logic into `src/`.
- Prioritize a structure that can be used immediately for actual training/evaluation/inference/analysis.
- If a request is ambiguous, do not assume; ask the minimum necessary questions.

[Default Directory Structure]
- The core structure must consist of `configs/`, `data/`, `scripts/`, and `src/`.
- If needed, additionally include `outputs/`, `logs/`, `checkpoints/`, `tests/`, and `notebooks/`.

[Directory Roles]
- `configs/`: Store experiment/model/data/training/augmentation/evaluation settings (YAML)
- `data/`: Store data (`raw/`, `interim/`, `processed/`, `external/` recommended)
- `src/`: Store reusable module code (e.g., `datasets/`, `models/`, `losses/`, `trainers/`, `evaluators/`, `metrics/`, `callbacks/`, `engine/`, `utils/`, `visualization/`, `postprocessing/`)
- `scripts/`: Handle only CLI entry points (argument parsing, config loading, calling `src`, execution orchestration)

[Configuration placement (entry layer vs library)]
- **Library code** (`src/` or equivalent importable package): expose functions, classes, and clear APIs. Avoid large module-level “default run” dictionaries that mix paths, hyperparameters, and UI flags—those belong at the boundary that invokes the library.
- **Structured training & formal evaluation**: keep reproducible experiment definitions in versioned config files under `configs/` (or the project’s chosen config store), loaded by thin entry scripts. Do not scatter the same hyperparameters as ad-hoc blobs inside `src/`.
- **Other runnable workflows** (inference, demos, benchmarks, ETL, visualization, ad-hoc analysis): define editable parameters in the **entry script** (CLI, app main, notebook setup cell)—e.g. argparse + a small settings object or dict—and pass them explicitly into `src`. Prefer one obvious place to edit when changing a run, not hidden defaults inside imported modules.
- **Runtime mutation** (global registries, singleton config): use sparingly; if unavoidable, document how callers must initialize state before calling into `src`.

[Code Writing Conventions]
- Whenever possible, write code in testable units separated by function/class.
- Avoid excessively large single files.
- Use clear English identifiers that reveal intent.
- Use `tqdm` for long-running loops in training/evaluation/inference scripts so progress is visible.
- For new training/evaluation/inference scripts, include a short description and an execution example at the top of the file.
- For training execution examples, include a log-saving example (e.g., `2>&1 | tee ...`).

[Path/Environment Conventions]
- Use project-root-relative paths by default.
- Prefer a structure compatible with the `pyrootutils` style.
- Separate path utilities into something like `src/.../utils/path*.py`.
- GPU device indices configured in YAML must always follow PyTorch CUDA indexing (`cuda:<index>`), not `nvidia-smi` physical ordering.
- If `CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES` is set, treat YAML GPU indices as re-mapped PyTorch indices after visibility filtering.
- When YAML includes `device.cuda_visible_devices`, `device.cuda_indices` must use local indices `[0..N-1]` relative to that visible set.
- For DDP runs, `len(device.cuda_indices)` must match `--nproc_per_node` (or `WORLD_SIZE`) to avoid invalid device ordinal errors.
- Avoid ambiguous GPU mapping in run docs: always state whether an index is `nvidia-smi` physical or PyTorch logical.

[Required Training Pipeline Features]
- Auto Batch Size (initial probe + automatic accumulation calculation if needed)
- Periodic Evaluation (intermediate validation based on `eval_freq`, save best checkpoint)
- Early Stopping (based on `patience`)
- Maintain EMA weights and use them for evaluation
- Standardized Resume (save/restore `last/best`, optimizer, scheduler, scaler, epoch, global_step, EMA state)
- Automatic reporting (`results.csv`, `results.json`, best metric summary, curve plot)
- Support AMP / DDP / Gradient Accumulation

[Experiment Artifact Conventions]
- Save outputs in a structured way under experiment-level directories.
- Recommended structure:
  - `outputs/<task_name>/<exp_name>/checkpoints/`
  - `outputs/<task_name>/<exp_name>/logs/`
  - `outputs/<task_name>/<exp_name>/figures/`
  - `outputs/<task_name>/<exp_name>/predictions/`
  - `outputs/<task_name>/<exp_name>/reports/`

[Response/Proposal Style]
- Prioritize directly applicable suggestions over abstract discussion.
- For architecture proposal requests, include the following:
  - recommended folder tree
  - explanation of folder roles
  - detailed `src/` structure
  - list of `scripts/` and their roles
  - training pipeline design
  - checkpoint/logging/output policy
  - naming conventions
  - example of `scripts -> src` calls